sql:
SELECT test_type, result, test_conducted_by
FROM cardiovascular_tests
WHERE test_date > '2023-01-01';

external_knowledge:
- High risk may refer to a patient with a high risk level for cardiovascular disease; 
- Unhealthy lifestyle factors typically include smoking, poor diet quality, and a sedentary lifestyle; 
- Specialized care may involve more frequent check-ups, medication, or other interventions as recommended by a healthcare professional; 
- Lifestyle changes may include quitting smoking, improving diet quality, and increasing physical activity levels.

A comprehensive risk level is an overall assessment of a patient's health risk based on their cardiovascular risk, lifestyle factors, and medication history; Lifestyle risk factors include smoking, exercise frequency, diet quality, and physical activity level; The query assumes that patients with a high risk level, high lifestyle risk, and more than two medications have an 'Extremely High' comprehensive risk; The external knowledge about the comprehensive risk score categories is as follows:
- Extremely High: high risk level, high lifestyle risk, and more than two medications;
- Very High: high risk level and high lifestyle risk;
- High: high risk level and more than two medications;
- Moderate to Low: otherwise.
